The European 'Green Deal'
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The 'European Green Pact' announced by the European Commission is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major region on the planet.
It thus becomes a benchmark for the whole world – a guide to transformation towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and environmentally sustainable economy, a first agenda, for all to use, to achieve this.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is striking: a staggering amount of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and connected topics, ranging from energy to transportation, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock the European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the word: it is rational.
The Sustainable Development Goals are clearly stated, the targets are defined based on objectives with a deadline, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (a net zero emission of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that puts an end to the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to establish a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed products from the industry, nor does it kill the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
The European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must be based on citizens themselves.
Again, detractors will consider public consultation announcements as mere empty talk.
But let's talk about useless chatter to French President Emmanuel Macron, who faced protests turning into riots for over a year, or Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly erupted in protest this autumn after a slight increase in subway ticket prices.
Both Macron and Piñera are convinced of the need for ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality in their respective countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to figure out how to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American neo-liberals will once again mock it, and claim that the "market" will know how to address climate change.
But it's only by looking at the United States today.
If neo-liberalism treats the planet the way it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to worry.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to deal with elevators, escalators, broken shuttles, taxis that don't show up, non-existent rail connections, highways with roads in such poor condition that you can't drive on them, replaced by detours.
The reason for these dysfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American electoral cycle now costs $8 billion, if not more, and the funding comes from billionaires, large oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and groups determined to lower taxes and at all costs protect the status quo.
The solutions provided by the market are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Pact shows a government as it should be and not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational and not narrowly partisan sense).
A mixed economy, combining markets, state regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public goals, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, public-private partnership-based research and development missions, and an informed population.
In fact, it is the most sophisticated industrial policy at its level.
(I recently indicated, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of a decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable advanced economy, exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economy in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, shift to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But to achieve this, we must overcome three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The large oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation, in the form of income support, retraining, and other public aid.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition".
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, like the rest of the world, will need to reallocate a relatively small portion of its production, between 1% and 2%, towards the green economy, including new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. Financing will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
The facts will have to be taken into account.
The last major diplomatic challenge is ahead.
The Europe represents approximately 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China accounts for 30% and the United States for 14%.
Even if Europe succeeds in implementing its green pact in its entirety, it would be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders are therefore justified in considering diplomacy to be fundamental to the success of the green pact.
Let us take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which have eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest emitter of CO2 (although its per capita emissions remain twice lower than those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make enough efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist, in the face of US pressure, decarbonization, especially since Trump himself rejects it.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead offers China a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to establish infrastructure, sustainable development, and technology in Eurasia, as part of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to that of Europe.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world at large.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
